Here's the recommended approach using **Window lifecycle events** and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom Window subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public App(NoteViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _viewModel);
}
```

### 3. Restore on first launch too

Load any previously saved draft in your ViewModel constructor:

```csharp
public class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    private string _draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);

    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set => SetProperty(ref _draftText, value);
    }
}
```

### Key things to remember

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **`Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch** | Initial sequence is `Created â†’ Activated`, so load saved state in the ViewModel constructor too |
| **Android back button skips `Stopped`** | Save in both `OnStopped` *and* `OnDestroying` |
| **Keep handlers fast** | `Preferences` is ideal â€” avoid DB writes here (Android ANR timeout is ~5s) |
| **`Deactivated` â‰  `Stopped`** | Don't save in `OnDeactivated` â€” it fires for dialogs/notification shade, not just backgrounding |
